76561198082358060,Recommended,312210,11554318,"Posted: 4 August, 2014",all,SonOfKonzan,"I bought The Fifth Day after watching one of PsiSyndicate's lets plays for it. He stated in his video that the game was poorly made, very buggy, and had little to no content. Still, I purchased it in hope of a half-way decent survival&building game.Once I launched it I was greeted with a pleasant surprise. The game's visuals were beautiful and captured the asthetic of a cold, lonely wasteland well and without any FPS drops or crashing on maximum settings. Once I started walking around the desolate world I came across a new breed of enemy, robots. The bots were well modeled and effectively frightining, as one of them slowly turned around; scanned me and shot one round. Killing me in my place. I must say I jumped as the shot rang out.Gameplay mechanics such and building and combat are fluid and difficult enough to provide a challenge, not a headache.To start building you must find a hacker tool (They mainly spawn in cities and towns), and a harvester. (Harvesters are found in pits around the map) If you do find a harvester, you must hack into it using the tool mentioned above. Once hacked you command the machine to collect resources and drop them near you (The way the harvester flys around and drops supply pods is impressive for a game this young). Once you have enough resources you build using a recipe book found around the map. The building itself is rather alot like the game ""Rust"" by Garry Newman, You craft templates and place them in a locking format. I prefer The Fifth Day's building more because it has no glitches with the terrain and more templates to produce more complex structures. Combat is wonderful, the weapon models sway with your charecter, the firearms themselves feel powerful and fun to fire, and the recoil is set properly to give you the satisfaction of a well aimed shot.The AI is not the smartest out there, but still provide enough of a challenge to keep you on the edge of your seet as you walk through the deserted countrysides and cities.All in all I give The Fifth Day a 10/10, for breathtaking visuals and atmosphere, no bugs or glitches, well designed building and gunplay mechanics, interesting and new hostile enemies, low hardware requirements, and low price."
